[Student "S"]
{You would really like to have a transfer bid in this situation, to make North bid \Hs.

But you don't have one, so you just bid 4\H yourself.

South plays 4\H. West leads the \ST. You play low in dummy and West holds the trick. He continues the suit and East takes the \SQ and then plays the \SA.

Loser List: \S = 2 : \H = 1 : \D = 0 : \C = 1 :: Total = 4

You've already lost the 2 \Ss. If West has the \HK you might avoid a loser there. You don't have a winner on which to discard the \C loser. 

If East has the \HK it will have to be a singleton to help you, so it is more logical to play West for the \HK.  But if West does have the \HK it will do you no good to ruff East's \SA, West will over-ruff and you would still have that \C loser. 

So do it this way instead. Discard the \C loser on East's \SA! Another \S from East won't hurt you since dummy would be able to over-ruff West. Whatever East plays you can win, then finesse West out of his \HK.

It was said earlier that you didn't have a winner on which you could discard the \C loser.

That was true, so instead you were able to discard it on a loser! }
[Play "W"]ST

